Using the aforementioned optimum conditions, N-CQDs fluorescence spectra in the presence of different Sul concentrations were studied. As seen (Fig. 6
                        A, B), the fluorescence intensity of the N-CQDs decreased with increasing Sul concentrations. The calibration curve (F/F0, F and F0 are the PL intensities of N-CQDs at 450 nm in the presence and absence of Sul) was linear in the concentration range, 0–200 μg/mL using the equation: y = −0.000447 ×  + 0.9809, with a determination coefficient (R2) of 0.9923. The limit of detection was 2 μg/mL when S/N was 3 [37,38]. As indicated, N-CQDs fluorescence intensity was reduced with increasing Sul levels. This phenomenon was probably due to the formation of hydrogen bonds between the oxygen atoms of OSO/CO in the Sul molecule and H and N (O) of –OH/NH2 on the surface of N-CQDs. This may have led to N-CQDs aggregation and quenched fluorescence [39–42] (Fig. 7
                        ).

It is accepted that CQDs can inhibit some bacteria [15,16]. However, anti-fungal and anti-oomycete activities remain under-reported. Thus, to evaluate the anti-pathogen activities of N-CQDs, we assessed two different pathogens. As indicated (Fig. 8
                        A and B), N-CQDs displayed a broad spectrum anti-fungicidal activity against two the phytopathogens, C. cassiicola and P. nicotianae; inhibitory rates were 82.8% and 75.3%, respectively, at 11 μL/mL N-CQDs. Similarly, an inhibitory efficiency of almost 100% was identified at 22 μL/mL. Also, with increasing N-CQD concentrations, C. cassiicola and P. nicotianae growth was gradually inhibited (Table 2
                        ).
